e":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Maltravers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Matravers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Matravers","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Mautravert in Chérencé-le-Héron (Manche)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":10,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":19,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Maltravers was born in 1205, in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England as the daughter of John de Maltravers II. She had at least 2 sons with Elias Giffard. She died in 1248, in her hometown, at the age of 43, and was buried in Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England."},"et":{"1205–1248":"1205–1248","1202–1257":"1202–1257","1208–1257":"1208–1257","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1180–1248":"1180–1248","1229–1299":"1229–1299","1232–1299":"1232–1299","1179–1262":"1179–1262","1262":"1262","19 January 1232":"19. jaanuar 1232","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1202":"1202","about 1229":"umbes 1229","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1299":"1299","1232":"1232","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England":"Brimpsfield, Gloucestershire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1205–1248":"1205–1248","1202–1257":"1202–1257","1208–1257":"1208–1257","1212–Male":"1212–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1180–1248":"1180–1248","1229–1299":"1229–1299","1232–1299":"1232–1299","1179–1262":"1179–1262","1262":"1262","19 January 1232":"19. tammikuuta 1232","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1202":"1202","about 1229":"noin 1229","1179":"1179","1212":"1212","1299":"129